{
  "answer": "**In \"The Wanderer\" (chapter 11 of *Old English Elegies*), the speaker refers to his lost personal lord/protector using several Old English kennings and compounds, with no single plain term like *dryhten* (\"lord\"). The most direct and recurring is *goldwine* (\"gold-friend\"), a poetic kenning for a generous ring-giving lord.**[^1][^2]\n\nThis appears first when the speaker laments: *siþþan geara iu goldwine minne / hrusan heolstre biwrah* (\"since long ago my gold-friend / the earth's darkness covered\").[^3]\n\nOther terms include:\n- *mondryhten* (\"liege-lord\" or \"protector-lord\"): *þæt he his mondryhten clyppe ond cysse* (\"that he his liege-lord / is clasping and kissing\").[^4]\n- *winedryhten* (\"wine-lord\" or \"friend-lord\"): *his winedryhtnes / leofes larcwidum* (\"his beloved lord's / wise counsel\").[^5]\n\nA plural reference to \"beloved protectors\" translates *leofra geholena* (\"dear helpers/saviors\").[^6]\n\n[^1]: *Unknown*, \"The Wanderer,\" *Old English Elegies*, ch. 11 (transliteration: [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/transliteration/#p-9bd9cc)).\n[^2]: *Unknown*, \"The Wanderer,\" *Old English Elegies*, ch. 11 (translation: [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9462cc)).\n[^3]: *Unknown*, \"The Wanderer,\" *Old English Elegies*, ch. 11 (original: [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/original/#p-9bd9cc)).\n[^4]: *Unknown*, \"The Wanderer,\" *Old English Elegies*, ch. 11 (original: [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/original/#p-9bd9cc)).\n[^5]: *Unknown*, \"The Wanderer,\" *Old English Elegies*, ch. 11 (original: [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/original/#p-9bd9cc)).\n[^6]: *Unknown*, \"The Wanderer,\" *Old English Elegies*, ch. 11 (translation: [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9462cc)).",
